	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>FAO guidelines on fish 'ecolabelling': a means to promote sustainable fishing?</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 March 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> The FAO Committee of Fisheries (COFI) adopted a set of voluntary guidelines for the ecolabelling of fish products on March 11th 2005.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> An 'ecolabel' is a tag placed on a product that certifies that it was produced in a sustainable, environmentally-friendly way. The new guidelines are aimed at providing guidance to governments and organisations that already maintain, or are considering establishing, labelling schemes for certifying and promoting labels for fish and fishery products from well-managed marine-capture fisheries.</p><p> 'We have seen a proliferation of ecolabels on various products, some of which have little credibility, confused consumers, caused unfair competition in the market place, and did not promote sustainable practices,' according to Ichiro Nomura, the FAO assistant director-general for fisheries. 'These are the kinds of challenges that the guidelines on ecolabelling of marine-capture fish products recently adopted by COFI can help address.'</p><p> The FAO guidelines acknowledge the hurdles that poorer countries face in responsibly managing their fisheries ,due to a lack of financial and technical resources, as well as the particular challenges posed by the small-scale fisheries common in many developing nations. The guidelines, therefore, call for financial and technical support for poorer countries to help them implement and benefit from ecolabelling schemes. However, adds Mr Nomura, it should be noted that some of the world's better managed fisheries are, in fact, found in developing countries. Ecolabelling can offer these countries better market opportunities and the possibility of larger export revenues, he says.</p><p> These guidelines come at a time when 52% of world stocks are fully exploited, which means they are being fished at their maximum biological productivity, 16% are overexploited and 7% are depleted, as shown in the FAO report on the state of world fisheries and aquaculture, released in early March 2005. With seven of the top ten marine fish species fully exploited or overexploited, serious biological and economic drawbacks are likely if fishing capacity for these stocks is further increased. It is hoped that ecolabelling will be a tool to achieve sustainable fishing.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.fao.org/newsroom/en/news/2005/100302/index.html" target="_self">FAO press release 'Ecolabelling schemes to support sustainable fisheries...</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=13555&amp;Cr=fishing&amp;Cr" target="_self">UN News Centre press release 'UN report warns of dangers of over-fishing...</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.globefish.org/index.php?id=2370" target="_self"><i>Globefish</i>, 'The state of world fisheries and aquaculture 2004',...</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Given the strong international demand for high-quality fishery products and relatively abundant fish stocks, what do ACP countries have to gain from ecolabelling scheme &quot;sll current indications are that ecolabelled fishery products could have a limited niche amongst particular consumer groups concerned with the sustainability of fish stocks. However, in practice such concerns have yet to make any impact on market behaviour. The main concerns of EU consumers would seem to be price and quality. To change this behaviour, considerable efforts are required to raise awareness amongst consumers about the benefits of purchasing fish that has been caught in ways that promote sustainability.</p><p> It is also apparent that in the main, the economic benefits from fisheries ecolabelling schemes accrue to the certifying agencies and to supermarket chains that provide the main retail outlets for fishery products in the EU. In many EU member states, as much as 70-90% of the retail sales of fresh and frozen fish are made through a small number of large supermarket chains. It is these large entities that stand to gain any economic rewards from ecolabelling schemes, and not fishing communities in ACP countries. The advice to ACP countries about ecolabelling of fishery products is therefore to 'watch this space', rather than to 'invest now'.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
